\begin_layout Title
Ability score allocation systems in RPGs
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subtitle
a treatment of the D&D point-buy system and generalizations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Stratos Kovalkov Papadoudis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
In this work we examine D&D5's ability score allocation variant (point-buy)
 system, how it works and what scorre palettes it yields as a result.
 We then generalize to other possible compatible systems to extract possible
 features a good score allocation system has.
 Finally after proposing natural extentions of D&D5's point-buy systems,
 we set down the rules for creating any (parametrized) custom system from
 scratch.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
D&D5's standard
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
D&D5's abilities
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Most RPGs nowadays follow an ability score system, by which a set of distinct
 abilities is assigned scores to quantify a character's said abilities.
 In this work we will follow the example of D&D5's score system as a template.
\end_layout

