reference "tab:point-buy"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 however, ther eis a complication: suddently for going from 13 to 14 requires
 2 points spent, so it is not exactly an ability allocation system per se,
 but one that relies on an 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

artificial
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 currency by which ability points may cost 1 or may cost more if score goes
 too high.
 This is common in other RPGs like the computer game 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Knights of the Old Republic
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 which makes higher 1 point increments even more costly.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This nonlinearity in costing ability scores allocation introduces some very
 interesting game balance aspects to a game.
 You stand to loose more than you normally would for every 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

high
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 score you pick, there is a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

loss
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in the exchange which is different to a balanced trade-off (without losses).
 Imagine as an analogy having three coins and tossing two of them to your
 friend, but one drops on the ground so they only get one.
 If the trade-off wasn't lossy, you should loose two coins and your friend
 should get 2 coins.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $+2$
\end_inset

s in the cost 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

schema
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 indicate that getting these high scores is a lossy trade-off in terms of
 ability points: for every high score point you add, you loose two low ability
 points, not one, due to the higher price of ability points added to high
 scores.
\end_layout

