\begin_layout Subsubsection
D&D5's schema advanced features
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Apart from the basic features that make a schema functional in a game, there
 are some finer details that actually make a particular schema more game-balance
d:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
increasing
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

cost
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

of
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

increment The lowest bound of 
\begin_inset Formula $+1$
\end_inset

 does not normally prevent highs and lows in costs of increments; for example
 a 
\begin_inset Formula $(\hphantom{+}0,+1,+2,+1,+2)$
\end_inset

 is a legit increment schema, however the logic of ramping the cost higher
 than the penalty entails the notion of tradeoff loss for obtaining something
 that is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

overpriced
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, and since higher scores not only are more valuable but they become exceedignly
 rare, it is natural to expect that cost of increments will only 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

increase
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 the more you go up.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
default
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

cutoff There is a natural cutoff setting for all schemas with the aforementioned
 features, called the half-volume cutoff.
 If one tries to get the maximum possible allowable scores (15) from D&D's
 standard schema for all 6 abilities, the total cost is 
\begin_inset Formula $6\cdot9=54$
\end_inset

 (the respective lowest cost being 0 by definition).
 At a first glance one could reject the half volume of 27 as a standard
 on account of the non-linearity of costs of acquisition; this in fact is
 a fallacy because, adjusting the cutoff to acount for cost non-linearities
 negates the desired effect of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

overpricing
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This is not very precise, as the nonlinearities are still present, but have
 much less of an impact when treated specifically by the cutoff.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If, however, the cutoff is adjusted to some value for any other reason,
 it makes it a legit choice, so this is more of a design aspect rather than
 a mathematicla restriction: if you mess with the cutoff be sure to do so
 for the right reasons.
\end_layout

