\begin_layout Subsection
Exploring the standard schema
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A schema like the ones discussed in effect defined a cost function on the
 domain of possible scores
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
integer score values assumed
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{cost}:\text{scores}\longrightarrow\mathbb{N}
\]

\end_inset

where the cost of acquisition is used.
 In this notation, the cutoff constraint in creating a score palette takes
 the form
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum\nolimits _{\text{score}\in\text{palette}}\text{cost}(\text{score})=\text{cutoff}
\]

\end_inset

Such a constraint dictates a (possibly lossy) trade-off logic in creating
 a score: if you push one value up, you have to drom some other values down
 to keep the cost the same, resulting in a restricted set of allowable score
 palettes.
 Such a logic has two characteristic palettes:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
a
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

median
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 that represents the most uniform score palette in the system (least score
 variance)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
an
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

extreme
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 that represents an 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

edgy
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 score palette (most score variance)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can build D&D's standard extreme palette by hand: start including maximum
 scores until the cutoff prevents adding more.
 In this case things are simple because 3 15s cost 
\begin_inset Formula $3\cdot9=27$
\end_inset

 and we 're done; the rest can only be 8, leading to 
\begin_inset Formula $(\hphantom{0}8,\hphantom{0}8,\hphantom{0}8,15,15,15)$
\end_inset

.
 This kind of extreme (half lows halfe highs) makes for an even finer requiremen
t for a schema, that is present by default in trivial schemas (costs of
 increments all 
\begin_inset Formula $+1$
\end_inset

) and in carefully designed non-tricial schemas, like that of D&D.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Producing the median is not as straightforward, because the average position
 of the median is affected by the non-linearity of costs of acquisition.
 Start by increasing all ability points in the palette by one till the cutoff
 can no longer support it; then add the remaining points to spent the entire
 cutoff.
 We can easily see that 6 12s cost 
\begin_inset Formula $6\cdot4=24$
\end_inset

 so we cannot proceed to 13; we can merely make 3 of them 13, leasding to
 
\begin_inset Formula $(12,12,12,13,13,13)$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
It only falls in the middle of the schema's score range if the costs of
 increment are constant, which implies linear costs of acquisition.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now it is understood that a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

perfect
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 form for the median is that of a purely uniform score palette, but that
 is not always possible.
 However, schemas using the default cutoff will always have extreme and
 median of the above form (split palettes in 3 and 3 uniform subpalettes).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If one deploys all possible score palettes in D&D's standard, they will
 find a total of 65, the default 
\begin_inset Formula $(\hphantom{0}8,10,12,13,14,15)$
\end_inset

 amongst them.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Extending the D&D standard
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An argument often heard by D&D players when choosing between rolling their
 ability scores or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

buying
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 them is that while the point-buy system always yields game-balanced palettes,
 its score spectrum is merely 3-15.
 On the otherhand, rolling the best 3d6 out of 4d6 while it gives you a
 good change at adequate scores, there is still a considerable (and uncontrollab
le) risk factor that may lead to an overpowered or an underpowered player,
 but the score spectrum is 3-18, and this is the only reason why players
 may chose rolling over buying.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So ideally there would be a point-buy system that has a greater score spectrum.
 The official word of Wizards of the Coast is that the final word falls
 to the GM.
 However the GM naturally is afraid that if they include a new score schema
 they might break game balance.
 The purpose of this analysis is to see how can one stem new balanced schemas
 from an original schema that is axiomatically balanced.
\end_layout

